{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":371,"record_hash":"sha256:79ad2039c592482b7dc9ab9dba66660a168a1a98391fef145b944d1e314c68cb","timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:36:30.108Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"`is_entrypoint` means: “this is the branch/stack segment GitButler thinks the current `HEAD` is focused on.”\n\nIn plain Git, it’s boring:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"stacks\": [\n    {\n      \"branches\": [\n        { \"name\": \"feature-x\", \"is_entrypoint\": true }\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nIn GitButler, the workspace can show several applied branches at once. Example:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"stacks\": [\n    {\n      \"branches\": [\n        { \"name\": \"bottom-refactor\", \"is_entrypoint\": false },\n        { \"name\": \"top-feature\", \"is_entrypoint\": true }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"branches\": [\n        { \"name\": \"side-fix\", \"is_entrypoint\": false }\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nThat says: these branches are visible in the workspace, but the user/agent was “on” or focused through `top-feature`.\n\nIt comes from `but_workspace`’s ref info model. A segment has `is_entrypoint`; `head_info(...).pruned_to_entrypoint()` can even narrow the view to that focused path. For agentlog, I’d keep the full visible workspace if possible, but mark the entrypoint branch/segment so scoring can boost it without pretending it’s the only relevant branch.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:36:30.108Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}